NAME: dauurica
AUTHOR: (Pallas, 1776).
TYPE_LOC: "Vivit in campis, montiumque declivibus arenosis apricis, per totam Dauuriam..." Restricted by Ellerman and Morrison-Scott (1951{#1282}:452) to "Kulusutai, Onon River, Eastern Siberia" [Chitinsk. Obl. Russia].
DISTRIB: Steppes from Altai, Tuva, and Transbaikalia (Russia) through N China and Mongolia, south to Qinghai Province, China.
STATUS_: Considered a pest, is intensively controlled in China; control in Russia has been much less intensive. Isolated populations around the margins of the Gobi Desert in China and Mongolia are very vulnerable (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: erythrotis
AUTHOR: (Bu[..]chner, 1890).
CITATION: Wiss. Result. Przewalski Cent. Asien Reisen. Zool. Th., B. I: Sa[..]ugeth., p. 165.
TYPE_LOC: Not specified; restricted by Allen (1938{#0653}:535) to "Burchan-Budda", East Tibet, China.
DISTRIB: E Qinghai, W Gansu, possibly N Sichuan, S Xinjiang, and Tibet (China).

NAME: forresti
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1923.
DISTRIB: NW Yunnan, SE Tibet (China); N Burma; Assam, Sikkim (India); Bhutan.

NAME: gaoligongensis
AUTHOR: Wang, Gong, and Duan, 1988.
TYPES: Institute of Epidemic Diseases (Dali, Yunnan) 107, skin, skull.
TYPE_LOC: "Dongsao-fang [Mount Gaoligong], (27<o>45'N, 98<o>27'E), Gongshan Co., Northwest Yunnan, alt. 2950 m." [China].
DISTRIB: Known only from the type locality.

NAME: gloveri
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1922.
DISTRIB: W Sichuan, NW Yunnan, NE Tibet, SW Qinghai (China).

NAME: himalayana
AUTHOR: Feng, 1973.
TYPE_LOC: "Qu-xiang, Bo-qu Valley, Nei-la-mu [= Nyalam] District, alt. 3500 m." [Xigaze (Shigatse) County, Xizang (Tibet), China].
DISTRIB: Mt. Jolmolunga (Everest) area, S Xizang, China; probably adjacent Nepal.

NAME: hyperborea
AUTHOR: (Pallas, 1811).
TYPE_LOC: "... e terris Tschuktschicis," [Chukotsk peninsula (Ognev, 1940{#1892}:41), Chukotsk A.O., Russia].
DISTRIB: Ural, Putorana, Sayan Mtns, east of Lena River to Chukotka, Koryatsk and Kamchatka; upper Yenesei, Transbaikalia, and Amur regions, Sakhalin Island (Russia); NC Mongolia; NE China; N Korea; Hokkaido (Japan).
STATUS_: Appears common throughout its large range.

NAME: iliensis
AUTHOR: Li and Ma, 1986.
TYPES: Ili Prefecture Health and Antiepidemic Station (Yining, Xinjiang) 83001, skin, skull; BEIJ 85003, paratype.
TYPE_LOC: "Tienshan Mountain [Borokhoro Shan], Nilka [County], Xinjiang, China, alt. 3200 m."
DISTRIB: Known only from the type locality (Li et al., 1988{#2899}).

NAME: koslowi
AUTHOR: (Bu[..]chner, 1894).
CITATION: Wiss. Reisen. Przewalski Cent. Asien Zool. Th. I: Sa[..]ugeth., pg. 187.
TYPES: ZIN 2729, -30, lectotype, paralectotype; skin, skull; 1 mounted skin, skull.
TYPE_LOC: "Dolina Vetrov" [Valley of the Winds; pass between Guldsha Valley and valley of Dimnalyk River, tributary of Chechen, Tarim Basin, Xinjiang, China, 14,000' (37<o>55'N, 87<o>50'E)].
DISTRIB: Arkatag Range, Kunlun Mtns (China).
STATUS_: IUCN - Vulnerable. Not found by recent expedition to type locality, but reported at Aqqikkol (37<o>09'N, 88<o>11'E)(Zheng, 1986{#2032}). Listed in "Red Book" of China.

NAME: ladacensis
AUTHOR: (Gu[..]nther, 1875).
TYPE_LOC: "Chagra, 14000 feet above the sea" [Changra, Ladak, Kashmir, India].
DISTRIB: SW Xinjiang, Qinghai, E Tibet (China); Kashmir (India); Pakistan.
STATUS_: Probably not scarce, but poorly known. May be affected by control measures directed at <^curzoniae^>.

NAME: macrotis
AUTHOR: (Gu[..]nther, 1875).
TYPE_LOC: "Doba" [C Tibet, (31<o>N, 87<o>E), China] Ognev (1940{#1892}:86). Not "Duba. . .N side. . .Kuenlun on road. . .via Kugiar" [Kakyar, [=]37<o>45'N, 77<o>05'E, W Xinjiang, China] <^contra^> Blanford (1879{#1957}:76). Not Dobo, Qinghai [(36<o><&>macrotis.ext
DISTRIB: Mountains of Sichuan and Yunnan (China); Himalayas (Nepal, India) from Bhutan through Tibet, Kunlun (China), Karakorum (Pakistan), Hindu Kush (Afghanistan), Pamir, and W Tien Shan Mtns (Kirghizistan, Tadzhikistan, SE Kazakhstan).

NAME: muliensis
AUTHOR: Pen and Feng, 1962.
CITATION: <^In^> Pen et al., Acta Zool. Sinica, 14 (supplement):120, 132.
TYPE_LOC: "Ting-Tung-Niu-Chang, southeastern Muli (alt. 3600m) Szechuan" [Muli A.D., Xichang County, Sichuan, China].
DISTRIB: Known only from the vicinity of the type locality.

NAME: nubrica
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1922.
DISTRIB: Southern edge of Tibetan Plateau from Ladak (India, China) through Nepal to E Tibet (China).

NAME: pallasi
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1867).
TYPE_LOC: "...said to come from 'Asiatic Russia-Kirgisen'" (Thomas, 1908{#2020}:109). Restricted by Heptner (1941{#1993}:328) to "southern parts...Karkaralinsk Mountains...north of Lake Balkhash" [Karagandinsk Obl., Kazakhstan ([=] 49<o>N, 75<o>E)].
DISTRIB: Discontinuous in arid areas (mtns and high steppes) in Kazakhstan; Altai Mtns, Tuva (Russia), and Mongolia, to Xinjiang and Inner Mongolia (China).
STATUS_: Isolated populations of <^O^>. <^p^>. <^hamica^> and <^O^>. <^p^>. <^sunidica^> are threatened, or in some cases may be extinct (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: princeps
AUTHOR: (Richardson, 1828).
TYPE_LOC: "Rocky Mountains"; restricted by Preble (1908{#2001}) to "near the sources of Elk (Athabasca) River," [Athabasca Pass, head of Athabasca River, Alberta, Canada].
DISTRIB: Mountains of W North America from C British Columbia (Canada) to N New Mexico, Utah, C Nevada, and EC California (USA).
STATUS_: Most populations are not currently threatened, except for a few isolates in the Great Basin (<^goldmani^>, <^obscura^>, <^nevadensis^>, <^tutelata^>); <^tutelata^> may now be extinct (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: pusilla
AUTHOR: (Pallas, 1769).
CITATION: Nova Comm. Imp. Acad. Sci. Petropoli, 13:531.
TYPE_LOC: "in campis circa Volgam..."; restricted by Ognev (1940{#1892}) to Samarsk Steppe, near Buzuluk, left bank of Samara River [Orenburgsk Obl. Russia].
DISTRIB: Steppes from middle Volga (Russia), east and south through N Kazakhstan to upper Irtysh River and Chinese border. Not yet recorded in China.
STATUS_: Disappearance from W end of its range within historic times was probably caused by elimination of preferred shrub-steppe habitat (Kuz'mina, 1965{#1881}). Some pop. are listed as rare in the "Red Book" of Bashkir Aut. Rep. (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: roylei
AUTHOR: (Ogilby, 1839).
CITATION: Royle's Illus. Botany...Himalaya, vol. 2, 69, pl. 4 [erroneusly labeled "<^Lagomys alpinus^>"].
TYPE_LOC: "Choor Mountain, Lat. 30. Elev. 11,500[ft], [60 mi. (96 km) N of Saharanpur], Punjab, India.
DISTRIB: Himalayan Mtns in NW Pakistan and India to Nepal; adjacent Tibet (China).

NAME: rufescens
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1842).
TYPES: BM(NH) 44.9.15.9.,-10., co- and lectotypes, skin; skin, skull.
TYPE_LOC: "India, Cabul, Rocky Hills near Baker Tomb at about 6000 or 8000 feet elevation" [Baber's (?) Tomb, Kabul, Afghanistan].
DISTRIB: Afghanistan, Baluchistan (Pakistan), Iran, Armenia, and SW Turkmenia.
STATUS_: Considered a crop pest and controlled in parts of its range. However, most populations are not considered threatened. A possible exception may be the isolated population of <^shukurovi^> in the Little Balkhan Range, Turkmenia (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: rutila
AUTHOR: (Severtzov, 1873).
TYPE_LOC: "...in mountains near Vernyi [Alma-ata]...7000-8000 ft." [2134-2438m]. Restricted by Shnitnikov (1936{#2013}) to valley of Maly Alma-atinsk River, Zailisk Alatau Mtns, Kazakhstan (43<o>05'N, 77<o>10'E).
DISTRIB: Isolated ranges from the Pamirs (Tadzhikistan) to Tien Shan (SE Uzbezistan, Kirghizistan, SE Kazakhstan); perhaps N Afghanistan and E Xinjiang (China).
STATUS_: This is a rare species, extremely sporadic in occurrence throughout its range, and common in only a few localities (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}).

NAME: thibetana
AUTHOR: (Milne-Edwards, 1871).
CITATION: Nouv. Arch. Mus. Hist. Nat. Paris, Bull., 7:93.
TYPE_LOC: "mountain near Moupin" [Baoxing, Ya'an County, Sichuan, China.].
DISTRIB: Shanxi, Shaanxi, W Hubei, Yunnan, Sichuan, S Tibet (China); N Burma; Sikkim (India); perhaps adjacent Bhutan and India.
STATUS_: <^O^>. <^t^>. <^sikimaria^> of Sikkim may be endangered by habitat destruction (Smith et al., 1990{#2016}). Other forms do not appear to be threatened.

NAME: thomasi
AUTHOR: Argyropulo, 1948.
TYPE_LOC: "Valley of Alyk-nor." Restricted by Formosov (in Smith et al., 1990{#2016}) to Alang-nor Lake, NE Qinghai, China (35<o>35'N, 97<o>25'E); see also Corbet (1978{#1084}).
DISTRIB: NE Qinghai, Gansu, and Sichuan (China).
STATUS_: IUCN - Indeterminate. Apparently rare and scattered in distribution.

NAME: Prolagus
AUTHOR: Pomel, 1853.
CITATION: Cat. Meth. Desc. Vert. Foss. dans le Bassin Hydro. Super. de la Loire et Surt. la Val. Aff. Prin., l'Allier. Paris. p. 43.
DISTRIB: Late Oligocene-Holocene, Europe.

NAME: sardus
AUTHOR: (Wagner, 1832).
DISTRIB: Mediterranean Isls of Corsica (France) and Sardinia (Italy); adjacent small islands.

NAME: Leporidae
AUTHOR: G. Fischer, 1817.
DISTRIB: Originally all continents except S South America and Australasia; now worldwide through introduction.

NAME: idahoensis
AUTHOR: (Merriam, 1891).
DISTRIB: SW Oregon to EC California, SW Utah, N to SW Montana (USA). Isolated population in WC Washington (USA).
STATUS_: The status of the isolated Washington population is uncertain. Varies from secure to IUCN - Vulnerable depending upon population (Chapman et al., 1990{#2898}).

NAME: monticularis
AUTHOR: (Thomas, 1903).
DISTRIB: C Karoo (31<o>22'S, 22<o>E), Cape Prov. (South Africa).
STATUS_: IUCN - Endangered. Now survives only in "dense, discontinuous karoid vegetation in the districts of Victoria West, Beaufort West and Frazerburg" ([=]86km[2]) (Duthie and Robinson, 1990{#1978}).

NAME: hispidus
AUTHOR: (Pearson, 1839).
TYPES: BM(NH) (?); originally in East India Company Museum, skin.
DISTRIB: S Himalaya foothills from Uttar Pradesh (India) through Nepal and West Bengal to Assam (India), and south through NW Bangladesh. Since 1951, there have been very few reports from Uttar Pradesh and Assam, see Santapau and Humayun (1960{#2012}), Mallinson
DISTRIB2: (1971{#1886}), and Ghose (1978{#1989}). Presently known distribution summarized by Bell et al. (1990{#1956}).
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered.

NAME: Lepus
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1758.
DISTRIB: North America south to Isthmus of Tehuantepec; virtually all of Africa and Eurasia.

NAME: alleni
AUTHOR: Mearns, 1890.
DISTRIB: SC Arizona (USA) to N Nayarit and Tiburon Isl (Mexico).
STATUS_: Populations appear stable in Arizona, but in Mexico require investigation (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: americanus
AUTHOR: Erxleben, 1777.
TYPE_LOC: "in America boreeli, ad fretum Hudsonis copiosissimus." Restricted by Nelson (1909{#1891}:87) to Fort Severn, Ontario, Canada.
DISTRIB: S and C Alaska (USA) to S and C coasts of Hudson Bay to Newfoundland and Anacosti Isl (introduced) (Canada), south to S Appalachians, S Michigan, North Dakota, NC New Mexico, SC Utah, and EC California (USA).
STATUS_: Although population densities fluctuate greatly, status secure nearly everywhere (Keith and Windberg, 1978{#1878}; Sinclair et al., 1988{#2014}).

NAME: arcticus
AUTHOR: Ross, 1819.
CITATION: Voy. Discovery, II; ed. 2, App. IV, p. 170.
TYPE_LOC: "Southeast of Cape Bowen" (Nelson, 1909{#1891}:61) [Possession Bay, Bylot Island, lat. 73<o>37'N, Canada].
DISTRIB: Greenland and Canadian arctic islands southward in open tundra to WC shore of Hudson Bay, thence northwestward to the west of Fort Anderson on coast of Arctic Ocean. Isolated populations in tundra of N Quebec and Labrador, and on Newfoundland (Canada).
STATUS_: Does not appear to be at risk presently (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: brachyurus
AUTHOR: Temminck, 1845.
TYPE_LOC: "...tout l'Empire mais surtout dans l'i[^]le de Jezo", Nagasaki, Kyushu, Japan.
DISTRIB: gonshu, Shikoku, Kyushu, Oki Isls and Sado Isl (Japan).
STATUS_: No indication of decline at present (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: californicus
AUTHOR: Gray, 1837.
TYPE_LOC: "St. Antoine" [probably near Mission of San Antonio, California, USA]. Discussed by Hall (1981{#0204}:326).
DISTRIB: Hidalgo and S Queretaro to N Sonora and Baja California (Mexico), north to SW Oregon and C Washington, S Idaho, E Colorado, S South Dakota, W Missouri, and NW Arkansas (USA). Apparently isolated population in SW Montana.
STATUS_: Secure; range is expanding at expense of <^L^>. <^callotis^> and <^L^>. <^townsendi^> (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: callotis
AUTHOR: Wagler, 1830.
TYPE_LOC: "Mexico"; restricted by Nelson (1909{#1891}:122) to southern end of Mexican Tableland.
DISTRIB: C Oaxaca (Mexico) north discontinuously to SW New Mexico (USA).
STATUS_: Appears to be relatively rare; classified as "endangered" in U.S. (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: capensis
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1758.
TYPE_LOC: "ad Cap. b. Spei" [South Africa, Cape of Good Hope].
DISTRIB: Africa in two separate, non-forested areas: South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Zimbabwe, S Angola, S Zambia (?), Mozambique; and to the north, Tanzania, Kenya, Somalia, Ethiopia, countries of the Sahel and Sahara, and N Africa; thence eastward through the
DISTRIB2: Sinai to the Arabian Peninsula, Jordan, S Syria, S Israel and W and S Iraq, west of the Euphrates River.
STATUS_: Populations have declined locally due to habitat alteration, but most are not threatened so far as is known (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: castroviejoi
AUTHOR: Palacios, 1977.
TYPE_LOC: "Puerto de la Ventana, San Emiliano (Leo[']n [Province])" [= Puerto Ventana, Spain, 1500 m].
DISTRIB: Cantabrian Mtns between Sierra de Ancares and Sierra de Pen[~]a Labra (N Spain).
STATUS_: Although it has a very restricted range (25-40 km by 230 km), it is common in most places (Palacios, 1983{#1893}).

NAME: comus
AUTHOR: Allen, 1927.
DISTRIB: Yunnan, W Guizhou (China).
STATUS_: Probably secure at present (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: coreanus
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1892.
DISTRIB: Korea; S Kirin, S Liaoning, E Heilungjiang (China).

NAME: corsicanus
AUTHOR: de Winton, 1898.
DISTRIB: Italy from the Abruzzo Mtns southward; Sicily; introduced into Corsica no later than 16th Century (Vigne, 1988{#2025}).
STATUS_: Unknown, but probable reduction in numbers and range due to overhunting and introduction of <^L^>. <^europaeus^> (Palacios et al., 1989{#1895}).

NAME: europaeus
AUTHOR: Pallas, 1778.
CITATION: Nova Spec. Quad. Glir. Ord., p. 30.
TYPE_LOC: Not stated; restricted by Trouessart (1910{#2023}), to Poland (see discussion in Ognev, 1940{#1892}:140, which further restricts it to SW Poland).
DISTRIB: Open woodland, steppe and subdesert: from S Sweden and Finland to Britain, throughout Europe (not Iberian Penin. south of Cantabria and the Ebro R, or south of Siena in Italy), to W Siberian lowlands; south to N Israel, N Syria, N Iraq, the Tigris-Euphra
DISTRIB2: tes valley and W Iran. SE border of range (Iran) from S Caspian Sea south to Persian Gulf (54<o>E); see Angerman (1983{#1948}:19). Introduced to Ireland, SE Canada-NE USA, S South America, Australia, New Zealand and several islands, including<&>europ.ext

NAME: fagani
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1903.
DISTRIB: N and W Ethiopia, and adjacent SE Sudan, south to extreme NW Kenya.

NAME: flavigularis
AUTHOR: Wagner, 1844.
TYPE_LOC: "Mexico" Restricted by Elliot (1905{#1979}:543) to San Mateo del Mar, Tehuantepec [City, Oaxaca, Mexico].
DISTRIB: Coastal plains and bordering foothills on south end of Isthmus of Tehuantepec (Oaxaca, Mexico), along Pacific coast to Chiapas (Mexico); now restricted to small area between Salina Cruz, Oaxaca, and extreme W Chiapas.
STATUS_: IUCN - Endangered, by habitat destruction and overhunting.

NAME: granatensis
AUTHOR: Rosenhauer, 1856.
DISTRIB: Iberian Peninsula, except NE and NC parts (Spain, Portugal); Mallorca (Balearic Isl, Spain).
STATUS_: Generally common, but scarce or extinct in a few places.

NAME: hainanus
AUTHOR: Swinhoe, 1870.
TYPE_LOC: Hainan Island, "in the neighbourhood of the capital city" [Hainan Province, China].
DISTRIB: Lowlands of Hainan Island.
STATUS_: Numbers reduced to extremely low levels by habitat alteration and overhunting, but no official status as yet conferred.

NAME: insularis
AUTHOR: W. Bryant, 1891.
TYPE_LOC: "Espiritu Santo Island, [near La Paz], Gulf of California [Baja California del Sur], Mexico."
DISTRIB: Restricted to the type locality.
STATUS_: IUCN - Rare. Occupies very small insular range, but population is stable, and seems in no danger (Chapman et al., 1983{#1969}).

NAME: mandshuricus
AUTHOR: Radde, 1861.
DISTRIB: Ussuri region (Russia); NE China; extreme NE Korea.

NAME: nigricollis
AUTHOR: F. Cuvier, 1823.
DISTRIB: Pakistan; India; Bangladesh, except Sunderbands; Sri Lanka; introduced into Java (?) and Mauritius, Gunnera Quoin, Anskya, Re[']union and Cousin Isls in the Indian Ocean. Considered native to Java by McNeely (1981{#1887}:931).
STATUS_: Mainland (and Sri Lankan?) populations secure (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}). If <^nigricollis^> is native to Java (rather than an introduced population), its numbers are now very low there.

NAME: oiostolus
AUTHOR: Hodgson, 1840.
TYPE_LOC: "...the snowy region of the Hemalaya, and perhaps also Tibet." Restricted by Kao and Feng (1964{#1876}), to "Southern Tibet" [Xizang, China].
DISTRIB: Tibetan Plateau, from Ladak to Sikkim (India) Nepal, and eastward through Xizang (Tibet) and Qinghai, Gansu and Sichuan (China).
STATUS_: Probably secure, but may be affected by rodent control activity on Tibetan Plateau.

NAME: othus
AUTHOR: Merriam, 1900.
DISTRIB: W and SW Alaska (USA); formerly perhaps northwestward to Pt. Barrow; as here interpreted, also E Chukotsk (Russia).
STATUS_: Rare, perhaps decreasing in range and numbers (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: peguensis
AUTHOR: Blyth, 1856.
DISTRIB: C, S Burma from Chindwin River valley east through Thailand; Cambodia; S Laos, S Vietnam; south in upper Malay Peninsula (Burma, Thailand) to 12<o>N.
STATUS_: Does not seem threatened (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: saxatilis
AUTHOR: F. Cuvier, 1823.
TYPE_LOC: "il habite les contre[']es qui se trouvent a[`] trois journe[']es au nord du cap de Bonne-Espe[']rance," [Cape of Good Hope, South Africa].
DISTRIB: Cape Province (and Zululand north to C Natal?) (South Africa) and S Namibia.
STATUS_: Appears common (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}), but this is uncertain (Angermann, in litt., 1992).

NAME: sinensis
AUTHOR: Gray, 1832.
TYPE_LOC: "China". Restricted to vicinity of Canton [Guanzhou, Guangdong Province, China].
DISTRIB: SE China from Yangtse River southward; Taiwan; disjunct in NE Vietnam.
STATUS_: Unknown, but probably affected by habitat modification.

NAME: starcki
AUTHOR: Petter, 1963.
TYPE_LOC: "Jeldu-Liban-Shoa, 2,740 me[`]tres, 40 km W.d' Addis v Abeba," [Ethiopia].
DISTRIB: C highlands of Ethiopia.
STATUS_: Numerous within its restricted range (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: timidus
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1758.
COMMON_NM: Eurasian arctic, white, or mountain, hare.
DISTRIB: Palearctic from Scandinavia to E Siberia, except E Chukotsk (Russia), south to Sakhalin and Sikhote-Alin Mtns (Russia); Hokkaido (Japan); Heilungjiang, N Xinjiang (China); N Mongolia; Altai, N Tien Shan Mtns; N Ukraine, E Poland, and Baltics; isolated po
DISTRIB2: pulations in the Alps, Scotland, Wales and Ireland. Introduced into England, Faeros and Scottish Isls.
STATUS_: Populations fluctuate, but none apparently threatened, except perhaps in Alps (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: tolai
AUTHOR: Pallas, 1778.
CITATION: Nova Spec. Quad. Glir. Ord., p. 17.
TYPE_LOC: "Caeterum in montibus aprecis campisque rupestribus vel arenosis circa Selengam..." Restricted by Ognev (1940{#1892}:162) to "...valley of the Selenga River...." [Russia].
DISTRIB: Steppes N of Caspian Sea southward along eastern shore of Caspian to E Iran; eastward through Afghanistan; Kazakhstan and S Siberia, Middle Asian republics to Mongolia; and W, C, and NE China.
STATUS_: Populations in China (and perhaps elsewhere) have declined due to intensified agriculture and increased use of pesticides (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: townsendii
AUTHOR: Bachman, 1839.
TYPE_LOC: "...on the Walla-walla...river"; restricted by Nelson (1909{#1891}:78) to Fort Walla Walla, [near present town of Wallula, Walla Walla Co., Washington].
DISTRIB: C Alberta and Saskatchewan east to extreme SW Ontario (Canada), south to SW Wisconsin, Iowa, NW Missouri, west through C Kansas to NC New Mexico, west to C Nevada, EC California (USA) and north to SC British Columbia (Canada).
STATUS_: Has withdrawn from parts of its southeastern (Wisconsin, Iowa, Missouri, Kansas, S Nebraska) distribution, perhaps because of habitat alteration. Stable in remainder of range (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: victoriae
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1893.
TYPE_LOC: "Nassa, Speke Gulf, S. Victoria Nyanza" [Lake, Tanzania].
DISTRIB: From Atlantic coast of NW Africa (Spanish Sahara, Mauritania, south to Guinea and Sierra Leone) eastward across Sahel to Sudan and extreme W Ethiopia; southward through E Africa (E Congo, W Kenya) to NE Namibia, Botswana, and Natal (South Africa). Small
DISTRIB2: isolated population in W Algeria.
STATUS_: Isolated population around Beni Abbe[']s, Algeria, "deserve[s] attention" (Flux and Angermann, 1990{#2896}).

NAME: yarkandensis
AUTHOR: Gu[..]nther, 1875.
TYPE_LOC: "neighbourhood of Yarkand" [15 mi E, Xinjiang, China].
DISTRIB: Steppes of Tarim Basin, S Xinjiang (China), around edge of Takla Makan desert.

NAME: netscheri
AUTHOR: (Schlegel, 1880).
DISTRIB: Sumatra [Indonesia].
STATUS_: IUCN - Indeterminate. "...apparently the rarest lagomorph. About a dozen museum specimens exist, collected between 1880 and 1916, and there has been only one confirmed sighting since then, in 1972." (Flux, 1990{#1985}).

NAME: cuniculus
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
DISTRIB: W and S Europe through the Mediterranean region to Morocco and N Algeria; original range probably limited to Iberia and perhaps NW Africa; introduced on all continents except Antarctica and Asia; see Gibb (1990{#1990}). Worldwide as domesticated forms.
STATUS_: The form <^huxleyi^> of the Atlantic and Mediterranean isls "may be endangered" (Gibb, 1990{#1990}).

NAME: furnessi
AUTHOR: (Stone, 1900).
TYPES: Wistar Institute 5314, skin, skull [now in ANSP?]
DISTRIB: Amami Isls (Amami-Oshima and Tokuno-shima) (S Japan).
STATUS_: U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered. Total population estimated at around 4,000 (Sugimura, 1990{#2019}).

NAME: marjorita
AUTHOR: (St. Leger, 1929).
DISTRIB: S Sudan, Uganda, Ruanda, Burundi, NE Zaire, Central African Republic, S Chad, disjunct population in Angola.

NAME: crassicaudatus
AUTHOR: (I. Geoffroy, 1832).
CITATION: Mag. Zool. Paris, 2:cl. 1, pl. 9 and text.
DISTRIB: SE South Africa; extreme S Mozambique.

NAME: randensis
AUTHOR: Jameson, 1907.
TYPE_LOC: "Observatory Kopje...Johannesburg...Witwatersrand Range, Transvaal... 5,900 ft." [1,798 m] [South Africa].
DISTRIB: Two disjunct areas: NE South Africa; E Botswana to extreme W Mozambique, Zimbabwe; and W Namibia, perhaps SW Angola.

NAME: rupestris
AUTHOR: (A. Smith, 1834).
TYPE_LOC: "South Africa, rocky situations" [probably Van Rhynsdorp District, Cape Province, South Africa.].
DISTRIB: Two disjunct areas: S and C South Africa, S Namibia; and E Africa, from N Malawi and E Zambia north through C Tanzania to SW Kenya.

NAME: diazi
AUTHOR: (Ferrari-Pe[']rez, 1893).
CITATION: <^In^> Diaz, Cat. Comision Geogr.-Expl. Repu[']blica Mexicana, Exposicion Intern, Columbia de Chicago, pl. 42.
TYPE_LOC: "near San Marti[']n Texmelusa[']n, northeastern slope of Volca[']n Iztacci[']huatl [Ixtacci[']huatl, Puebla], Mexico."
DISTRIB: Distrito Federal, Mexico, and W Puebla (Mexico), in three discontinuous areas on the slopes of Volca[']n Pelado, Tlaloc, Popocate[']petl, and Ixtacci[']huatl.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered.

NAME: aquaticus
AUTHOR: (Bachman, 1837).
TYPE_LOC: "...western parts of that state" [Alabama]. Restricted by Nelson (1909{#1891}:272) to "Western Alabama".

CITATION: Darst. Sa[..]ugeth., text: "<^Mephitis^> <^mesoleuca^>" [not paginated] pl. 44, fig. 2.{#0382}
TYPE_LOC: "Gegend von Chico in Mexico" [Mexico, Hidalgo, near El Chico].
DISTRIB: Arizona, Colorado, Texas (USA), south to Nicaragua.

NAME: semistriatus
AUTHOR: (Boddaert, 1785).
TYPE_LOC: "Mexico"; Cabrera (1958{#1008}) listed the type locality as "Minas de Montuosa, cerca de Pamplona, departamento del norte de Santander, Colombia".
DISTRIB: Veracruz, Tabasco, and Yucatan (Mexico) to Peru and E Brazil.

NAME: Mephitis
AUTHOR: E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire and G. [Baron] Cuvier, 1795.

NAME: macroura
AUTHOR: Lichtenstein, 1832.
TYPE_LOC: "Gebirgs-Gegenden nordwestlich von der Stadt Mexico." [Mexico, mountains NW of Mexico City].
DISTRIB: S Arizona, S New Mexico, and W Texas (USA), through Mexico to Costa Rica.

NAME: mephitis
AUTHOR: (Schreber, 1776).
DISTRIB: SW Northwest Territories to Hudson Bay and S Quebec (Canada), south to Florida (USA), N Tamaulipas, N Durango, and N Baja California (Mexico).

NAME: Spilogale
AUTHOR: Gray, 1865.
TYPE_SPEC: <^Mephitis^> <^interrupta^> Rafinesque, 1820 (= [<^Viverra^>] <^putorius^> Linnaeus, 1758) by monotypy (Melville and Smith, 1987{#0209}).

NAME: putorius
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
TYPE_LOC: "America septentrionali" restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}), to "South Carolina." [USA].
DISTRIB: SW Canada east to Minnesota and S Pennsylvania (USA); south to Costa Rica.

NAME: pygmaea
AUTHOR: Thomas, 1898.
DISTRIB: Sinaloa to Oaxaca (Mexico).

NAME: Mustelinae
AUTHOR: G. Fischer, 1817.
ORIG_NM: Mustelini G. Fischer, 1817, corrected to Mustelidae by Gill (1872{#0003}).

NAME: barbara
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
DISTRIB: Sinaloa and Tamaulipas (Mexico), south to Argentina, including: Brazil, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Guatemala, Guyana, Honduras, Mexico, Nicaragua, Panama, Peru, Venezuela, Argentina, Belize, Bolivia, Surinam, and Trinidad.

NAME: cuja
AUTHOR: (Molina, 1782).
TYPE_LOC: "Chili" restricted by Thomas (1912{#0788}) to "S. Chili (Temuco)"; Cabrera (1958{#1008}) restricted the locality to "alrededores de Santiago" [Chile]. Honacki et al. (1982{#0119}) listed the type locality for <^G. c. furax^> Thomas, 1912.
DISTRIB: Argentina, Bolivia, Peru, Brazil, Chile, Paraguay.

NAME: vittata
AUTHOR: (Schreber, 1776).
DISTRIB: San Luis Potosi and Veracruz (Mexico) to Peru and S Brazil, at lower elevations, including: Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Costa Rica, Guatemala, Guyana, Panama, and Venezuela.

NAME: Gulo
AUTHOR: Pallas, 1780.
TYPE_SPEC: <^Gulo^> <^sibiricus^> Pallas, 1780 (= [<^Mustela^>] <^gulo^> Linnaeus, 1758), by absolute tautonymy (Melville and Smith, 1987{#0209}).

NAME: gulo
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
TYPE_LOC: "alpibus Lapponi[ae], Ruffiae, Sibiriae, sylvis vastissimis", restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}) to "Lapland".
DISTRIB: Holarctic taiga and S tundra, south to 50<o>N (Eurasia) and 37<o>N (North America).

NAME: libyca
AUTHOR: (Hemprich and Ehrenberg, 1833).
CITATION: Symb. Phys. Mamm., vol. 1, pt. 2, sig. K, verso.{#0394}
DISTRIB: Fringes of the Sahara Desert from Morocco and Egypt on the north, and from Mauretania and N Nigeria to Sudan on the south.

NAME: striatus
AUTHOR: (Perry, 1810).
CITATION: Arcana, Mus. Nat. Hist., Signature Y, Fig. [41][1810]{#0468}.
TYPE_LOC: "South America". This is clearly in error and Hollister (1915{#0387}) fixed the type locality as "Cape of Good Hope". [South Africa].
DISTRIB: Senegal to SE Egypt and Ethiopia, south to South Africa, including: Botswana, Kenya, Malawi, Namibia, Nigeria, South Africa, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda, and Zimbabwe.

NAME: patagonicus
AUTHOR: (Blainville, 1842).
TYPE_LOC: Listed in Cabrera (1958{#1008}) as "cercani[']as del ri[']o Negro." [Argentina].
DISTRIB: Argentina and S Chile.

NAME: americana
AUTHOR: (Turton, 1806).
DISTRIB: Alaska and Canada south to N California, south in the Sierra Nevada and Rocky Mtns to 35<o>N.

NAME: flavigula
AUTHOR: (Boddaert, 1785).
TYPE_LOC: Not given; fixed by Pocock (1941{#0085}) as "Nepal".
DISTRIB: Primorski Krai (Russia); Korea; China, west along Himalayan foothills to NW Pakistan; isolates in S India, SE Asia, Taiwan, Sumatra, Java, and Borneo.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix III (India); U.S. ESA - Endangered as <^M^>. <^f^>. <^chrysospila^>; IUCN - Indeterminate as <^M. f. chrysospila^>.

NAME: foina
AUTHOR: (Erxleben, 1777).
TYPE_LOC: "Europa inque Persia", listed by Miller (1912{#0827}) as "Germany."
DISTRIB: From Spain to S and C Europe, through Caucasus Mtns, to the Altai (Russia, Kazakhstan), Mongolia, and Himalayas; adjacent China; islands of Corfu, Crete and Rhodes.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix III (India) as <^M. f. intermedia^>.

NAME: gwatkinsii
AUTHOR: Horsfield, 1851.
CITATION: Cat. Mamm. Mus. E. India Co. p. 90.{#0106}
DISTRIB: S India.

NAME: martes
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
DISTRIB: Britain and Ireland; N and W Europe to W Siberia, south to Sicily, Sardinia, Corsica, the Elburz Mtns (Iran), and the Caucasus Mtns.

NAME: melampus
AUTHOR: (Wagner, 1841).
DISTRIB: Japan (Honshu, Kyushu, Shikoku, Tsushima, introduced on Sado Isl); Korea.

NAME: pennanti
AUTHOR: (Erxleben, 1777).
TYPE_LOC: "in America boreali, vulgaris victitans quadrupedibus minoribus." Listed by Miller and Rehm (1901{#1045}) as "Eastern Canada."
DISTRIB: Yukon to E Quebec (Canada), NW USA, Sierra Nevadas, N Rocky Mtns, Great Lakes Region, New England, to North Carolina (USA).

NAME: zibellina
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
COMMON_NM: Sable; see Ognev (1935{#0445}) for a list of common names.
TYPE_LOC: "asia septentrionali," restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}) to "N. Asia." Restricted by Ognev (1935{#0445}) to "Tobol'skuyu gub. v ee severnoi chasti" ["northern part of Tobol'sk Province" (1962{#0686} translation)] [Russia].
DISTRIB: Ural Mtns to Siberia, Kamchatka, Sakhalin (Russia); Mongolia; Sinkiang and NE China; N Korea; Hokkaido (Japan); originally west to N Scandanavia and W Poland.

NAME: africana
AUTHOR: Desmarest, 1818.
CITATION: Nouv. Dict. Hist. Nat., Nouv. ed., 9:376.{#0094}
TYPE_LOC: "Africa", type locality is in error, fixed by Cabrera (1958{#1008}) as "arrabales de Belem, la antigua Para[']." [Brazil]
DISTRIB: Amazon Basin in Brazil, Ecuador, and Peru.

NAME: altaica
AUTHOR: Pallas, 1811.
DISTRIB: E Kazakhstan, S and SE Siberia, Primorski Krai (Russia); Mongolia; Tibet, W and N China; Korea.

NAME: erminea
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1758.
TYPE_LOC: "Europa and Asia frigidiore; hyeme praefertim in alpinis regionibus nivea".
DISTRIB: Circumboreal, tundra and forested regions of Palearctic, south to the Pyrenees, alpine Slovenia, Alps, Caucasus, W Himalayas, and Xinjiang (China); N Mongolia, N China; and C Honshu (Japan); and, in the Nearctic south to C California, N New Mexico, N Iow
DISTRIB2: a and Maryland (USA). Introduced to New Zealand.

NAME: eversmannii
AUTHOR: Lesson, 1827.
TYPE_LOC: "trouve[']...entre Orembourg et Bukkara," restricted by Stroganov (1962{#0568}:338) to "basseinu sredneyo techeniya r. Ileka, ...r. Bol'shoi Khobdy" [Russia, Orenburg Obl., S of Orenburg, mouth of Khobda River, a tributary of Ilek River.]
DISTRIB: Steppes and subdeserts of E Europe, and republics of the former USSR; Mongolia; W, C and NE China.

NAME: felipei
AUTHOR: Izor and de la Torre, 1978.
TYPE_LOC: "Santa Marta, elevation 2,700 m, near San Agustin, Huila, Colombia".
DISTRIB: The type locality and Cauca, Colombia (two localities separated by 70 km, on opposite sides of Cordillera Central.

NAME: frenata
AUTHOR: Lichtenstein, 1831.
CITATION: Darst. Sa[..]ugeth., text:"Das geza[..]umte Wiesel" [not paginated], and plate 42{#0382}.
DISTRIB: S Canada to Venezuela and Bolivia, excluding the SW deserts of the USA.

NAME: kathiah
AUTHOR: Hodgson, 1835.
DISTRIB: Himalayas from N Pakistan through Nepal to Burma; S and E China; Indochinese Peninsula.

NAME: lutreola
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1761).
DISTRIB: NE Spain, France; disjunct populations throughout Europe to the Irtysh and Ob Rivers (Russia, Kazakhstan).

NAME: lutreolina
AUTHOR: Robinson and Thomas, 1917.
TYPES: BM(NH) 17.8.4.2; skin and skull of an adult male.
TYPE_LOC: "Tjibodas, West Java, 5500'"; identified by Van Bree and Boeadi (1978{#0697}) as "6<o>44'S 107<o>00'E".
DISTRIB: Indonesia (Java, Sumatra).

NAME: nigripes
AUTHOR: (Audubon and Bachman, 1851).
TYPE_LOC: "lower waters of the Platte River", restricted by Hayden (1863{#0826}:138) to "Fort Laramie" [Wyoming, USA].
DISTRIB: Formerly, S Alberta and Saskatchewan (Canada) south to Arizona, Oklahoma, and NW Texas (USA). Viable populations now only in captivity.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered.

NAME: nivalis
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1766.
DISTRIB: The Palearctic (excl. Ireland, the Arabian Peninsula, and Arctic Isls); Japan; the Nearctic in Alaska (USA), Canada, and USA, south to Wyoming and North Carolina. Introduced to New Zealand; see Corbet and Hill (1980{#0139}).

NAME: nudipes
AUTHOR: Desmarest, 1822.
TYPE_LOC: "L'i[^]le de Java". Locality is in error, fixed by Robinson and Kloss (1919{#0087}) as "West Sumatra" [Indonesia].
DISTRIB: Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia (Sumatra, Java, Borneo).

NAME: putorius
AUTHOR: Linnaeus, 1758.
TYPE_LOC: "inter Europae rupes et lapidum acervos", restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}) to "Scania, S. Sweden."
DISTRIB: Europe (excluding Ireland and most of Scandinavia), east to the Ural Mtns.

NAME: sibirica
AUTHOR: Pallas, 1773.
TYPE_LOC: "Sibiriae montanis, sylvis densissimis", restricted by Pocock (1941{#0085}) to "Vorposten Tigerazkoi, near Usstkomengorsk, W. Altai," based on Pallas (1773{#0245}:570). Listed in Honaki et al. (1982{#0119}) as "U.S.S.R., E. Kazakhstan, vic<&>sibirica.ext
DISTRIB: Russia (Tataria, Dalnevostochny Rayon), Ural Mtns, Siberia; Pakistan east to N Burma; N Thailand; Taiwan; China; Korea; Japan; introduced to Sakhalin, Russia.

NAME: strigidorsa
AUTHOR: Gray, 1855.
TYPE_LOC: Not given. Gray (1853{#0325}) based the type description on a manuscript given to him by Hodgson. Horsfield (1855{#0744}) later fixed the type locality as, "the Sikim Hills of Tarai." [India, Sikkim].
DISTRIB: Nepal east through Burma, Yunnan (China) and Thailand to Laos.

NAME: vison
AUTHOR: Schreber, 1777.
TYPE_LOC: "Man findet das Vison in Canada un Pensilvanien".
DISTRIB: North America from Alaska and Canada through all of USA except SW deserts. Introduced to Iceland, NC Europe, British Isls, Norway, Belarussia, Baltic States, Spain, and Siberia.

NAME: albinucha
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1864).
CITATION: Proc. Zool. Soc. Lond., 1864:69, plate X{#0367}.
TYPE_LOC: "it was without any habitat". Fixed by Coetzee (1977{#0017}) as "Cape Colony".
DISTRIB: South Africa, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Botswana, Namibia, Malawi, Zambia, Angola, Zaire, Rwanda, Burundi, Uganda, Tanzania, Kenya.

NAME: Vormela
AUTHOR: Blasius, 1884.
TYPE_SPEC: <^Mustela^> <^sarmatica^> Pallas, 1771 (= <^Mustela peregusna^> Gu[..]ldensta[..]dt, 1770), by original designation (Melville and Smith, 1987{#0209}).

NAME: peregusna
AUTHOR: (Gu[..]ldensta[..]dt, 1770).
CITATION: Nova Comm. Imp. Acad. Sci. Petropoli, 14(1):441.{#0696}
TYPE_LOC: "habitat in campis apricis desertis Tanaicensibus". Listed in Honacki et al. (1982{#0119}) as "U.S.S.R., Rostov Obl., steppes at lower Don River."
DISTRIB: Steppes and deserts of SE Europe, Caucasus, Kazakhstan, Middle Asia; SW Asia (excl. Arabia); N China and S Mongolia.

NAME: Taxidea
AUTHOR: Waterhouse, 1839.
TYPE_SPEC: <^Ursus^> <^Meles^> <^labradorius^> Gmelin, 1788 (= <^Ursus^> <^taxus^> Schreber, 1777), by original designation. (Melville and Smith, 1987{#0209}).

NAME: taxus
AUTHOR: (Schreber, 1777).
TYPE_LOC: "Er wohnt in Labrador und um die Hudsonsbay," restricted by Long (1972{#0492}), to "Carman, Manitoba." [Canada].
DISTRIB: SW Canada, British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatschewan, Manitoba, Ontario, to Baja California and Puebla (Mexico), east to Lake Ontario.

NAME: Otariidae
AUTHOR: Gray, 1825.
ORIG_NM: Otariina, corrected to Otariidae by Gill (1866{#0359}).

NAME: Odobenidae
AUTHOR: Allen, 1880.
CITATION: U.S. Geol. and Geog. Surv. Territ., 12:ix, 5.{#0241}

NAME: rosmarus
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
DISTRIB: Arctic seas: south as far as New England (USA), Great Britain, Scandinavia, Pribilof Isls, and Honshu (Japan) at least occasionally.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix III (Canada); IUCN - Insufficiently known as <^O. r. laptevi^>.

NAME: Arctocephalus
AUTHOR: E. Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire and F. Cuvier, 1826.
TYPE_SPEC: "<^Phoca ursina^> " (= <^Phoca pusilla^> Schreber, 1777; not <^Phoca ursina^> Linnaeus, 1758; Allen, 1905{#0822} discussed confusion in designation of type species).

NAME: australis
AUTHOR: (Zimmermann, 1783).
TYPE_LOC: Zimmermann (1783{#0610}) based the name on the "Falkland Isle Seal" of Pennant (1781{#0322}), however, he added that it "Wohnt um Juan Fernandez, und u[..]ber haupt in dortigen Meeren." [Falkland Isls, UK].
DISTRIB: Coasts of South America from Lima (Peru) to Rio de Janeiro (Brazil); Falkland Isls.

NAME: forsteri
AUTHOR: (Lesson, 1828).
CITATION: <^In^> Bory de Saint-Vincet (ed.), Dict. Class. Hist. Nat. Paris, 13:421. {#0343}
TYPE_LOC: Scheffer (1958{#0520}) restricted the type locality to "Dusky Sound, New Zealand."
DISTRIB: New Zealand and nearby subantarctic isls; S and W Australia.

NAME: galapagoensis
AUTHOR: Heller, 1904.
TYPES: Natural History Museum, Stanford Univ. 2812 skull only of an adult male.
DISTRIB: Specimens recorded only from Galapagos Isls [Ecuador].

NAME: gazella
AUTHOR: (Peters, 1875).
CITATION: Monatsb. K. Preuss. Akad. Wiss. Berlin, 1875:393, 396.{#0703}
TYPE_LOC: "von Seehunden aus Kerguelenland". Restriced by Scheffer (1958{#0520}) to "Anse Betsy (49<o>09'S, 70<o>11'E)."
DISTRIB: Islands south of Antarctic convergence (Kerguelen, S Sandwich, S Orkney, Heard, Bouver, S Georgia, S Shetland Isls).

NAME: philippii
AUTHOR: (Peters, 1866).
CITATION: Monatsb. K. Preuss. Akad. Wiss. Berlin, 1866:276, pl. 2a, b, c. {#0466}
TYPES: skin and skull, lost by fire in World War II (Scheffer, 1958{#0520}).
TYPE_LOC: "Insel Juan Fernandez". Listed by Scheffer (1958{#0520}) as "Isla Ma[']s a Tierra, Islas Juan Ferna[']ndez, Chile".
DISTRIB: Specimens recorded from Juan Fernandez and San Felix Isls (Chile).

NAME: pusillus
AUTHOR: (Schreber, 1775).
TYPE_LOC: Unknown. "Diese Gattung findet sich in den levantischen, und nach dem Herrn Grafen von Bu[..]ffon, im indischen Meere"; discussion of type locality in Allen (1880{#0241}).
DISTRIB: SW Africa from Angola to Algoa Bay; SE Australia; Tasmania.

NAME: townsendi
AUTHOR: Merriam, 1897.
TYPE_LOC: "Guadalupe Island, off Lower California. . . collected on the beach on west side of Guadalupe." [Mexico]
DISTRIB: Guadalupe Isl (Mexico), Channel Isls (California, USA).
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA - Threatened; IUCN - Vulnerable.

NAME: tropicalis
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1872).
TYPE_LOC: "North coast of Australia." This is in error, fixed by King (1959{#0887}) to "<< Australasian sea >>...to include the islands of St. Paul and Amsterdam as these are the islands nearest to Australia...".
DISTRIB: Islands north of Antarctic Convergence (Tristan, Gough, Marion, Crozet, Amsterdam, Macquarie Isls).

NAME: ursinus
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
COMMON_NM: Northern, Pribilof, or Alaska fur seal (English);
TYPE_LOC: "in Camschatc[ae] maritimus inter Asiam and Americam proximam, primario in infula Beringri," restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}) to "Bering Island."
DISTRIB: North Pacific, in Okhotsk and Bering Seas; Commander and Pribilof Isls (Russia), south to Japan, Shantung (China), and S California (USA).

NAME: Eumetopias
AUTHOR: Gill, 1866.
TYPE_SPEC: "<^Otaria californiana^> Lesson., = <^Arctocephalus monterienis^> Gray." (= <^Phoca jubata^> Schreber, 1776).

NAME: jubatus
AUTHOR: (Schreber, 1776).
TYPES: None.  See Allen (1880{#0241}), and comments under type species for <^Eumetopias^>.
TYPE_LOC: "...Aufenthalt in dem no[..]rdlichen Theil des stillen Meeres...westlichen Ku[..]ste von Amerika... o[..]stlichen von Kamtschatka...Inseln...Ku[..]sten unter dem 56ten Grade der Breite liegen." [N part of the Pacific. Russia, Commander and Bering Isls].
DISTRIB: N Pacific, from Hokkaido (Japan) to S California (USA).

NAME: cinerea
AUTHOR: (Pe[']ron, 1816).
DISTRIB: Houtmans Abrolhos (Western Australia) to Kangaroo Isl (South Australia).

NAME: byronia
AUTHOR: (Blainville, 1820).
CITATION: J. Phys. Chim. Hist. Nat. Arts Paris, 91:300{#0190}.
TYPES: Osteological Coll., no. 3966 (Flower, 1884{#0848}). Destroyed during World War II (Scheffer, 1958{#0520}).
TYPE_LOC: "the island of Tinian...situe[']e a[`] l'est des Philippines ou par le 15<o> de latitude me[']ridionale et le 215<o> de long. me[']ridionale de Greenwich." This is an error, as there are no sea lions on these islands, fixed by Scheffer (195<&>byronia.ext
DISTRIB: South American coasts from Peru to Uruguay; Falkland Isl; occasionally north to coast of Brazil.

NAME: Phocarctos
AUTHOR: Peters, 1866.
CITATION: Monatsb. K. Preuss. Akad. Wiss. Berlin, 1866:269. {#0466}

NAME: hookeri
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1844).
TYPES: BM(NH) - 1843.11.25.2,336A, adult female, skeleton and skull.
TYPE_LOC: "Falkland Islands and Cape Horn."  Locality in error; fixed by Clark (1873{#0871}) as "Auckland Islands. . . between 800 and 900 miles S. of Tasmania, in lat. 50<o>48'S., long. 166<o>42'E." [New Zealand]
DISTRIB: Subantarctic islands of New Zealand.

NAME: californianus
AUTHOR: (Lesson, 1828).
CITATION: <^In^> Bory de Saint-Vincet (ed.), Dict. Class. Hist. Nat. Paris, 13:420. {#0343}
TYPE_LOC: "les rochers dans le voisinage de la baie San-Francisco sont ordinairement couverts de lion marins." [USA, California, San Francisco Bay].
DISTRIB: N Pacific from near the Mexico-Guatemala border to British Columbia (Canada); Japan; Galapagos Isls (Gallo-Reynosa and Solorzano-Velasco, 1991{#0824}).

NAME: Phocidae
AUTHOR: Gray, 1821.
ORIG_NM: Phocadae, corrected to Phocidae by Gray (1825{#0362}).

NAME: cristata
AUTHOR: (Erxleben, 1777).
TYPE_LOC: "Habitat in Groenlandia australiori et Newfoundland". [S Greenland and Newfoundland].
DISTRIB: N Atlantic and Arctic oceans, from Newfoundland (Canada) to S Greenland, Svalbard and Novaya Zemlya (Russia); occasionally south to Portugal and Florida (USA).

NAME: barbatus
AUTHOR: (Erxleben, 1777).
TYPE_LOC: "ad Scotiam atque Groelandiam australiorem, vulgaris circa Islandiam" [North Atlantic, S Greenland].
DISTRIB: Circumpolar Arctic seas (Canada, Greenland, Japan, Norway, USA, republics of the former USSR), south to Hokkaido (Japan) and Newfoundland.

NAME: grypus
AUTHOR: (Fabricius, 1791).
DISTRIB: Temperate and subarctic waters around Britain, Canada (Newfoundland area), Iceland, Greenland, Norway, Russia (Kola Peninsula), and Baltic Sea.

NAME: leptonyx
AUTHOR: (Blainville, 1820).
CITATION: J. Phys. Chim. Hist. Nat. Arts Paris, 91:298. {#0190}
TYPE_LOC: "des environs des i[^]les Falckland ou Malouines" [Falkland Isls (UK)].
DISTRIB: Circumpolar, in southern oceans (Antarctica, Australia, Chile, Kerguelen Islands, South Sandwich Isls, Falkland Isls, southern Africa, New Zealand).

NAME: weddellii
AUTHOR: (Lesson, 1826).
TYPE_LOC: "sur les co[^]tes des Orcades australes, situe[']es sour 60 degre[']s 37 minutes de lat" [South Orkney Isl (Br. Antarct. Trust Terr.)].
DISTRIB: Coastal fast ice areas of Antarctic continent and adjacent islands; occasionally north to South America, Australia, and New Zealand.

NAME: carcinophagus
AUTHOR: (Hombron and Jacquinot, 1842).
CITATION: <^In^> Dumont d'Uville, Voy. Pole Sud., Zool., Altas: Mammife[`]res, pl. 10 [1842], vol. 3:Mammife[`]res et Oiseaux, p. 27 [1853].
TYPE_LOC: "capture['] sur les glaces du Pole Sud, entre les i[^]les Sandwich et les i[^]les Powels, a[`] 150 lieues de distance de chacune de ces i[^]les." [Scotia Sea (midway between South Orkney and South Sandwich Isls) (Br. Antarct. Trust Terr.)].
DISTRIB: Antarctic seas, frequently on pack ice around Antarctic Continent, limited records from New Zealand, Australia, Tasmania, and Argentina.

NAME: angustirostris
AUTHOR: (Gill, 1866).
TYPES: Lectotype, designated by Poole and Schantz (1942{#0689}) as - USNM 4704, skull of immature female.
TYPE_LOC: "California" restricted by Poole and Schantz (1942{#0689}) to "St. Bartholomews Bay, lower California, Mexico." Clarified by Scheffer (1958{#0520}) as "Bahi[']a To[']rtola (= Bahi[']a San Bartolome[']) 27<o>39'N, 114<o>51'W, Baja California, Mexico".
DISTRIB: SE Alaska to California (USA) and Baja California (Mexico).

NAME: leonina
AUTHOR: (Linnaeus, 1758).
TYPES: None (Scheffer, 1958{#0520}).  BM(NH) - 1946.8.9.1, desgnited as neotype by Hamilton (1940{#0855}).
TYPE_LOC: "ad polum Antarcticum" restricted by Thomas (1911{#0192}) to "Juan Fernandez", further restricted by Hamilton (1940{#0855}) as "Isla Mas a Tierra" [Chile].
DISTRIB: Subantarctic islands, including Macquarie, Kerguelen, S Georgia Isls.

NAME: monachus
AUTHOR: (Hermann, 1779).
TYPE_LOC: King (1956{#0863}) listed the locality as "captured in the autumn of 1777 in the Dalmation Sea at Ossero." [Yugoslavia].
DISTRIB: Mediterranean and Black Seas; NW Africa to Cape Blanc.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered.

NAME: schauinslandi
AUTHOR: Matschie, 1905.
TYPES: Zoologisches Museum Humboldt 32795, skull and skin.
TYPE_LOC: "Laysan ist eine kleine Koralleinsel, nordwestlich der Sandwich-Inseln" [USA, Laysan Isl, 25<o>50'N, 171<o>50'W].
DISTRIB: NW Hawaiian Isls, from Nihoa to Kure.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA and IUCN - Endangered.

NAME: tropicalis
AUTHOR: (Gray, 1850).
CITATION: Cat. Spec. Mamm. Coll. Br. Mus., Part 2(Seals), p. 28{#0624}.
TYPE_LOC: "Jamaica" restricted by King (1956{#0863}) to "Pedro Cays, 80 km. south of Jamaica".
DISTRIB: Caribbean Sea and Yucatan.
STATUS_: CITES - Appendix I; U.S. ESA - Endangered; IUCN - Extinct?.

NAME: rossii
AUTHOR: Gray, 1844.
TYPE_LOC: "Antarctic ocean", restricted by Barrett-Hamilton (1902{#2944}) to "pack ice, north of Ross Sea 68<o>S, 176<o>E".
DISTRIB: Circumpolar, Antarctic pack ice, particularly King Haakon VII Sea.

NAME: caspica
AUTHOR: Gmelin, 1788.
TYPE_LOC: "in mari, praesertim septentrionali, etiam Pacifico et Caspico" [Caspian Sea].
DISTRIB: Caspian Sea.

NAME: fasciata
